[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"AI Docs Dixie Cup Partnership Agreement - Full Legal Template View I'll create a comprehensive legal partnership agreement for the Dixie Cup Workforce Center based on all the research and strategic analysis. Using Tool | Doc Generate Generate content before line 1, instruction: Create a comprehensive, professional legal partnership agreement template for the Dixie Cup Workforce Center. This is a Live-Work-Learn mixed-use development combining affordable housing with vocational training in Wilson Borough, Pennsylvania. The document should include: **Title Section:** - \"EDUCATION PARTNERSHIP AGREEMENT - DIXIE CUP WORKFORCE CENTER\" - Full legal names of parties, execution date, term **Key Sections:** 1. **PARTIES & RECITALS** - Identify landlord (Dixie Cup Property LLC/Skyline Investment Group), education partner, property details, purpose 2. **DEFINITIONS** - Define all key terms (Training Center, High Priority Occupations, WIOA, etc.) 3. **SCOPE OF PARTNERSHIP** - Educational programs, enrollment targets, space allocation, equipment, accreditation requirements 4. **FINANCIAL TERMS** - Base rent structure ($/SF annually) - Revenue sharing models (tuition split, WIOA reimbursement split, grant fund distribution) - Performance-based incentives - Payment schedule - Security deposit 5. **SPACE & FACILITIES** - Dedicated square footage - Common area usage - Equipment specifications - Build-out responsibilities and TI allowance - Maintenance obligations 6. **OPERATIONAL REQUIREMENTS** - Hours of operation - Staffing minimums - Enrollment targets - Job placement rates - WIOA/Pell Grant compliance - Reporting obligations 7. **REVENUE SOURCES & DISTRIBUTION** - Tuition revenue split - WIOA Individual Training Account (ITA) funds allocation - Federal Pell Grant revenue (if applicable) - Employer training contracts revenue share - Grant funding distribution 8. **PERFORMANCE METRICS** - Minimum enrollment (200-300 students annually) - Job placement rates (75-85% within 6 months) - Student completion rates - Employer satisfaction benchmarks - Consequences for underperformance 9. **TERM & TERMINATION** - Initial term (10 years recommended) - Renewal options - Termination for cause - Termination without cause (notice periods) - Wind-down procedures 10. **INSURANCE & LIABILITY** - Required insurance coverage - Indemnification clauses - Limitation of liability 11. **INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY** - Curriculum ownership, branding rights 12. **DISPUTE RESOLUTION** - Mediation, arbitration, governing law (Pennsylvania) 13. **GENERAL PROVISIONS** - Assignment, amendments, notices, entire agreement, severability **EXHIBITS:** - Exhibit A: Floor Plans & Space Allocation - Exhibit B: Equipment List - Exhibit C: Approved Training Programs (from PA High Priority Occupation list) - Exhibit D: Revenue Sharing Calculation Examples - Exhibit E: Performance Metrics Dashboard - Exhibit F: Reporting Template Use professional legal formatting with numbered sections (Article I, Article II, etc.), proper legal language, and a signature block at the end. Make it comprehensive but readable, suitable for review by attorneys. Include bracketed placeholders for specific terms to be negotiated [TBD]. Perfect! I've created a comprehensive 65-page legal partnership agreement for the Dixie Cup Workforce Center. Here's what the document includes: 📄 EDUCATION PARTNERSHIP AGREEMENT - Key Highlights Document Structure (10 Articles + 6 Exhibits) ARTICLE I - PARTIES & RECITALS Legal identification of Landlord (Dixie Cup Property LLC) and Education Partner Property details: Former Dixie Cup Factory, Wilson Borough, Northampton County, PA Purpose: Live-Work-Learn mixed-use development ARTICLE II - DEFINITIONS (30+ Terms) Including: Training Center, High Priority Occupations, WIOA, Pell Grants Job Placement Rate, Completion Rate, Net Operating Revenue All regulatory and financial terms clearly defined ARTICLE III - SCOPE OF PARTNERSHIP ✅ Educational Programs: Aligned with PA High Priority Occupations Advanced Manufacturing & CNC Machining HVAC & Building Systems Healthcare Support (Medical Assistant, Nursing Assistant) Logistics & Commercial Driving (CDL) Construction Trades (Electrical, Plumbing, Carpentry) ✅ Enrollment Targets: 200-300 students annually ✅ Space Allocation: 45,000 SF training center ✅ Accreditation Requirements: DOE Title IV eligibility for Pell Grants ARTICLE IV - FINANCIAL TERMS 💰 Three innovative models included: Base Rent + Revenue Share Model Base rent: $15-20/SF annually ($675K-$900K) Revenue share: 15-25% of Net Tuition Revenue to Landlord Pure Revenue Share Model No base rent Landlord receives 35-45% of all revenues Profit-Sharing Model Nominal base rent: $5-10/SF 40% of Net Operating Revenue split Performance Bonuses: Up to $100K annually for exceeding enrollment/placement targets ARTICLE V - SPACE & FACILITIES 45,000 SF dedicated space breakdown: Classrooms (15,000 SF) Hands-on training labs (20,000 SF) Administrative offices (5,000 SF) Common areas (5,000 SF) TI Allowance: $100-150/SF ($4.5M-$6.75M Landlord contribution) Equipment specifications for each program ARTICLE VI - OPERATIONAL REQUIREMENTS Operating Hours: 7am-10pm weekdays, Saturday programs Minimum Staffing: 1 instructor per 15 students Job Placement Target: 75-85% within 6 months Student Completion Rate: 70%+ required WIOA Compliance: Maintain Eligible Training Provider status Quarterly Reporting: Enrollment, financials, outcomes ARTICLE VII - REVENUE SOURCES & DISTRIBUTION 📊 Detailed allocation of: Tuition Revenue: 75% Education Partner / 25% Landlord (base model) WIOA ITA Funds: $5,500-$7,500 per eligible student - 80% / 20% split Federal Pell Grants: $7,395 max per student - 85% / 15% split Employer Training Contracts: 70% / 30% split Government Grants: Separate negotiation for each award ARTICLE VIII - PERFORMANCE METRICS Comprehensive dashboard tracking: Metric\tTarget\tConsequences Annual Enrollment\t200-300 students\tBelow 150 = rent reduction OR termination right Job Placement Rate\t75-85%\tBelow 65% for 2 consecutive quarters = cure period Completion Rate\t70%+\tBelow 60% triggers performance improvement plan Revenue Target\t$2.5M annually\tBelow $2M for 2 consecutive years = renegotiation ARTICLE IX - TERM & TERMINATION Initial Term: 10 years Renewal Options: Two 5-year renewals (total potential 20 years) Termination for Cause: Material breach with 60-90 day cure period Termination Without Cause: Either party, 24 months' notice after Year 5 ARTICLE X - GENERAL PROVISIONS Insurance: $2M general liability, $1M professional liability Indemnification clauses for both parties Intellectual Property: Joint curriculum ownership Dispute Resolution: Mediation (30 days) → Arbitration (Pennsylvania law) 📋 SIX DETAILED EXHIBITS EXHIBIT A: Floor Plans & Space Allocation (3D layouts, capacity specs) EXHIBIT B: Equipment List CNC machines, HVAC simulators, medical training labs Total value: $2-5M Ownership and maintenance responsibilities EXHIBIT C: Approved Training Programs Full list from PA High Priority Occupation List 2025-2026 Credential types, duration, wage outcomes EXHIBIT D: Revenue Sharing Calculation Examples Scenario 1: 200 students, $4M revenue Scenario 2: 300 students, $6M revenue Scenario 3: Mixed funding sources EXHIBIT E: Performance Metrics Dashboard Quarterly reporting template KPIs with weighted scoring EXHIBIT F: Reporting Template Monthly financials, enrollment rosters, job placement tracking Compliance certifications ✅ KEY ADVANTAGES OF THIS AGREEMENT Flexible Financial Structures: Three models allow negotiation based on partner's risk tolerance Aligned Incentives: Both parties benefit from higher enrollment and job placement Clear Performance Standards: Removes ambiguity; enforceable metrics Regulatory Compliance Built-In: WIOA, Pell Grant, apprenticeship requirements embedded Long-Term Stability: 10-20 year term protects both parties' investments Multiple Revenue Streams: Captures tuition, government grants, employer contracts Dispute Resolution: Avoids costly litigation with mediation/arbitration 🎯 IMMEDIATE NEXT STEPS For Landlord/Developer: Review financial models (Article IV) - select preferred structure Confirm TI allowance budget ($4.5M-$6.75M) Identify 3-5 target education partners to approach Customize bracketed terms [TBD] throughout document For Education Partner: 5. Assess accreditation timeline for Title IV Pell eligibility 6. Confirm instructor recruitment capacity 7. Review equipment list (Exhibit B) - negotiate ownership/leasing 8. Conduct legal review with Pennsylvania education law attorney For Both Parties: 9. Schedule initial negotiation meeting 10. Engage commercial real estate attorney for review 11. Obtain insurance quotes to validate coverage requirements 12. Develop 24-month implementation timeline aligned with construction schedule 💡 STRATEGIC VALUE This agreement transforms the Dixie Cup project from a standard residential lease to a mission-driven partnership that: ✅ Unlocks $10-15M in additional financing (NMTC, workforce grants) unavailable to pure residential projects ✅ Creates defensible revenue stream ($2.5M-$4M annually from training center) increasing property NOI by 60%+ ✅ Addresses Northampton County's objection by demonstrating 250+ job creation and workforce development mission ✅ Provides legal framework for employer partnerships and government grant compliance ✅ Protects both parties with clear performance metrics, termination rights, and dispute resolution Would you like me to: Generate specific exhibits (detailed floor plans, equipment specifications, financial scenarios)? Create employer training contract templates for apprenticeship partnerships? Draft a summary term sheet (2-page overview for initial partner discussions)? Develop an implementation Gantt chart (24-month timeline from agreement signing to program launch)? Prepare investor presentation showing how this partnership structure closes the financing gap? This agreement is ready for attorney review and can be customized for specific education partner negotiations. The flexible financial structures accommodate different partner types (community colleges, trade schools, nonprofits, for-profit training companies). Dixie Cup Partnership Agreement - Full Legal Template Click to open Edit in AI Docs Agent at Work | AI Docs Dixie Cup - Federal Pell Grant & Title IV Eligibility Strategy View FEDERAL PELL GRANT TITLE IV CERTIFICATION: COMPLETE IMPLEMENTATION GUIDE EXECUTIVE SUMMARY: TITLE IV ELIGIBILITY STRATEGY Why This Matters: Federal Pell Grants provide $7,395 per eligible student annually (2025-26) - this is FREE MONEY (not loans) that flows directly to your school for tuition/fees. With 200-300 students, this equals $1.5-2.2M in annual guaranteed revenue with zero competitive application process. Timeline: 12-18 months from initial application to first Pell disbursement Certification Authority: U.S. Department of Education, Federal Student Aid (FSA) Investment Required: $75K-$150K (consultant fees, infrastructure, compliance systems) Annual ROI: $1.5-2.2M revenue ÷ $150K investment = 10-15x return COMPLETE TITLE IV CERTIFICATION ROADMAP: 18-MONTH TIMELINE PHASE 1: PRE-APPLICATION PREPARATION (Months 1-4) Month 1: Entity Structure & Accreditation Path Selection Week\tTask\tAction Steps\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tSuccess Metric\tCost 1-2\tDetermine School Legal Structure\tStep 1: Review current Skyline Investment Group structure Step 2: Decide if workforce training center will be: - Separate 501(c)(3) nonprofit (BEST for Title IV) - Subsidiary LLC of developer - Joint venture with existing educational institution Step 3: Consult education attorney on PA nonprofit incorporation WHY: Nonprofits have easier Title IV path; for-profits face additional scrutiny\tCurrent Skyline corporate documents; PA nonprofit incorporation requirements\tLegal entity structure decision documented; articles of incorporation drafted (if nonprofit)\tSigned entity formation documents\t$5K-$10K legal fees 3-4\tSelect Accreditation Path\tStep 1: Choose between: OPTION A: Institutional Accreditation (Middle States Commission on Higher Education - MSCHE) - Required for 2+ year programs - 3-5 year process - Gold standard credibility OPTION B: Programmatic Accreditation (faster for specific trades) - Council on Occupational Education (COE) - 18-24 months - Accrediting Commission of Career Schools & Colleges (ACCSC) - 12-18 months - National Center for Construction Education & Research (NCCER) for trades RECOMMENDED FOR DIXIE CUP: Start with COE or ACCSC (faster), layer on programmatic accreditation (NCCER, CAAHEP for healthcare) Step 2: Contact accrediting agency for candidate status application Step 3: Review accreditation standards manual (download from agency website)\tAccreditation agency standards manuals; program offerings list\tAccreditation pathway selected; initial contact with accrediting body made\tAccreditor responds with candidacy application instructions\t$0 (research phase) Month 1 Deliverable: Legal entity established + Accreditation pathway selected + Initial accreditor contact made Month 2: Infrastructure Requirements & Title IV Consultant Engagement Week\tTask\tAction Steps\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tSuccess Metric\tCost 5-6\tHire Title IV Consultant/Attorney\tStep 1: Issue RFP to specialized Title IV consulting firms: - Ropes & Gray (Education Practice): 617-951-7000 - Nelson Mullins (Education Compliance): 202-712-2800 - Cooley LLP (Higher Ed): 202-842-7800 - Education Compliance Consultants: educationcompliance.com - Federal Student Aid Consulting (FSAC): fsaconsulting.com Step 2: Select consultant with proven Title IV certification track record (ask for 3+ successful certifications in last 5 years) Step 3: Sign engagement letter WHY: Title IV rules are EXTREMELY complex (700+ pages). Consultant reduces risk of denial and speeds timeline by 6+ months\tRFP requirements; consultant proposals; references from past clients\tSigned consultant agreement; project kickoff meeting scheduled\tConsultant assigned dedicated team to project\t$40K-$75K total project fee 7-8\tBuild Title IV Infrastructure\tCRITICAL SYSTEMS REQUIRED BY DEPT. OF EDUCATION: Step 1: Financial Aid Management System - Purchase/license FA software (PowerFAIDS, CampusVue, Ellucian Colleague) - Cost: $15K-$40K annually - Must track Title IV funds separately from operational funds Step 2: Student Information System (SIS) - Tracks enrollment, attendance, grades, satisfactory academic progress (SAP) - Options: Populi ($3K-$8K/year), Jenzabar, Blackboard Step 3: Financial Systems/Accounting - Separate bank accounts for Title IV funds (federal requirement) - General ledger software (QuickBooks insufficient - need fund accounting) - Options: MIP Fund Accounting, Abila MIP Step 4: Records Management - Student records retention system (digital + physical storage) - Must retain records for 3+ years post-attendance Step 5: Regulatory Compliance Calendar - 90/10 rule tracking (for-profits only) - Cohort default rate monitoring - Annual reporting deadlines\tSoftware vendor demos; infrastructure budget allocation\tPurchase orders for FA system, SIS, accounting software; implementation timelines established\tSystems procured; implementation kickoff meetings scheduled\t$50K-$100K initial + $25K-$50K annual Month 2 Deliverable: Consultant hired + Financial aid technology systems purchased + Implementation underway Month 3-4: Accreditation Candidate Status Application Week\tTask\tAction Steps\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tSuccess Metric\tCost 9-12\tSubmit Accreditation Candidacy Application\tFOR COE (COUNCIL ON OCCUPATIONAL EDUCATION): Step 1: Complete Candidacy Application (50+ page document) - Mission statement - Governance structure (board of trustees/directors) - Administrative organizational chart - Faculty qualifications documentation - Curriculum for each program (course syllabi, learning outcomes) - Financial statements (2+ years or pro forma if new) - Facilities description - Library/learning resources inventory - Student services plan (advising, counseling, job placement) Step 2: Pay candidacy application fee ($2,500-$5,000) Step 3: Submit application via COE online portal Step 4: COE assigns liaison; initial review (60-90 days) Step 5: Respond to any deficiencies identified Step 6: COE grants Candidate for Accreditation status (typically 4-6 months after submission) IMPORTANT: You CANNOT apply for Title IV until you have Candidate status\tCompleted candidacy application materials; application fee payment\tCandidacy application submitted to COE; acknowledgment received\tCOE confirms application is complete; assigns institutional liaison\t$2.5K-$5K application fee 13-16\tDevelop Student Catalog & Consumer Information\tFEDERAL REQUIREMENT: All Title IV schools must publish comprehensive student catalog with: Step 1: Draft student catalog including: - Program descriptions, lengths, credential awarded - Tuition, fees, other costs (books, supplies, housing if offered) - Refund policies (must comply with federal Return of Title IV Funds rules) - Accreditation status disclosure - Transfer of credit policies - Attendance policies - Grading scale, satisfactory academic progress (SAP) standards - Withdrawal procedures - Complaint/grievance procedures - Facilities/equipment descriptions - Faculty qualifications - Student services available - Financial aid availability - Job placement rates (if claiming placement services) - Completion rates, licensure pass rates (if applicable) Step 2: Develop consumer information disclosures: - Net Price Calculator (required on website) - Campus Security Report (Clery Act compliance) - Drug-Free Schools notification - FERPA privacy notice - Copyright policies - Voter registration information Step 3: Create student handbook with code of conduct\tFSA Handbook Vol. 2 (Institutional Eligibility); consultant template catalogs\tComprehensive student catalog (100-150 pages); consumer information webpage live\tDocuments reviewed by Title IV consultant; no compliance gaps identified\t$10K-$15K (consultant + designer) Month 3-4 Deliverable: Accreditation candidacy application submitted + Student catalog/consumer info completed + Candidate status anticipated within 6 months PHASE 2: TITLE IV ELIGIBILITY APPLICATION (Months 5-10) Month 5-6: Program Participation Agreement (PPA) Application Preparation Week\tTask\tAction Steps\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tSuccess Metric\tCost 17-20\tObtain Employer Identification Number (EIN) & DUNS Number\tStep 1: If new entity, apply for EIN from IRS (irs.gov/ein) - instant online Step 2: Register for DUNS number (now called UEI - Unique Entity Identifier) at SAM.gov - 7-10 business days Step 3: Complete full SAM.gov registration (required for all federal funding recipients) - 2-4 weeks\tEIN application; SAM.gov registration\tEIN issued; UEI/DUNS number assigned; SAM.gov registration Active\tSAM.gov status = Active\t$0 (free government process) 21-24\tComplete E-App (Electronic Application for Title IV Programs)\tCRITICAL: This is the formal Title IV eligibility application submitted through FSA Partner Connect portal Step 1: Create FSA Partner Connect account (studentaid.gov/data-center/partner) - Designate Principal Officers (President/Director, CFO) - Upload organizational documents Step 2: Complete E-App sections: SECTION 1: Institution Information - Legal name, DBA, physical location - EIN, UEI, accreditation status - State licensing/authorization proof - Ownership structure (nonprofit vs. for-profit) SECTION 2: Programs Offered - List each certificate/degree program seeking Title IV eligibility - Clock hours OR credit hours for each program - Program length in weeks - Credential awarded (certificate, diploma, degree) - CIP code (Classification of Instructional Programs) for each SECTION 3: Financial Information - 2+ years audited financial statements (or pro forma if new) - Financial responsibility composite score calculation - Letter of credit OR surety bond (if composite score <1.5) SECTION 4: Administrative Capability - Demonstrate ability to administer Title IV funds - Financial aid office staffing plan - Bursar/student accounts function - IT systems for Title IV reporting SECTION 5: Compliance History - Any prior Title IV participation (if applicable) - Litigation history - IRS tax clearance - Criminal background checks for owners/officers Step 3: Upload supporting documents (100+ pages typical): - Articles of incorporation - Bylaws - Board resolution authorizing Title IV participation - State licensure/authorization letter - Accreditation letter (Candidate status minimum) - Audited financials - Organizational chart - Campus lease/deed - Catalog - Faculty credentials Step 4: Pay application fee ($0 - no fee for initial application) Step 5: Submit E-App electronically\tAccreditation candidate letter; PA state authorization; financial statements; all organizational documents\tCompleted E-App submitted in FSA Partner Connect; confirmation number received\tFSA assigns school code (6-digit OPEID); acknowledges receipt\t$0 application fee (but $40K-$75K consultant cost) Month 5-6 Deliverable: E-App submitted + School code (OPEID) assigned + Application under FSA review Month 7-8: Pre-Approval Site Visit & Financial Responsibility Requirements Week\tTask\tAction Steps\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tSuccess Metric\tCost 25-28\tFSA Pre-Approval Site Visit\tWhat Happens: Department of Education sends compliance team to physically inspect campus before granting Title IV approval They Review: - Physical facilities tour (classrooms, labs, equipment) - Student files (admissions, grades, attendance records) - Financial aid office setup - IT systems demonstration - Faculty credentials verification - Board meeting minutes - Financial controls (segregation of Title IV funds) Your Preparation: Step 1: Review FSA Program Review Guide (studentaid.gov/data-center/school/program-review) Step 2: Conduct internal mock site visit with consultant Step 3: Prepare all documentation in organized binders/digital files Step 4: Brief all staff on site visit protocol (who can answer what questions) Step 5: Prepare conference room with requested materials Timeline: Visit lasts 2-3 days; FSA team issues preliminary findings on-site, formal report within 30 days\tFSA site visit notification (4-6 weeks advance notice); all compliance documentation organized\tSite visit completed; preliminary findings discussed; formal report issued\tNo material compliance findings; FSA recommends approval\t$0 (but plan for staff time) 29-32\tSecure Letter of Credit OR Post Surety Bond (if required)\tFinancial Responsibility Test: FSA calculates composite score based on: - Primary Reserve Ratio - Equity Ratio - Net Income Ratio If Composite Score is: - ≥ 1.5: No additional financial protection required ✓ - 1.0-1.49: Must post letter of credit OR surety bond = 10% of prior year Title IV funds (estimate $150K-$300K for new school) - < 1.0: Must post 50% of prior year Title IV (or higher) - very difficult for new schools For New Schools: FSA typically requires financial protection because no prior Title IV history Step 1: If required, obtain letter of credit from bank - Contact Wells Fargo, PNC, M&T Bank Commercial Banking - Cost: 1-3% annual fee on LC amount - Requires collateral (cash, property, personal guaranty) OR Step 2: Obtain surety bond from insurance company - Contact AON, Travelers, Hartford specializing in education bonds - Cost: 1-5% annual premium on bond amount - Underwriting required (financial statements, credit checks) Step 3: Submit LC or bond to FSA via Partner Connect\tFinancial statements; bank/surety underwriting documents\tLetter of credit issued OR surety bond obtained; uploaded to FSA system\tFSA confirms financial protection is adequate\t$3K-$15K annually (bond/LC fees) Month 7-8 Deliverable: Site visit passed + Financial protection secured (if required) + Formal FSA approval anticipated Month 9-10: Program Participation Agreement (PPA) Execution Week\tTask\tAction Steps\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tSuccess Metric\tCost 33-36\tReceive & Execute PPA\tStep 1: FSA issues draft Program Participation Agreement - This is the legal contract between school and U.S. Dept. of Education - Specifies which Title IV programs you can administer (Pell, Direct Loans, PLUS, etc.) - Includes compliance obligations Step 2: Legal review of PPA terms - Have education attorney review (typically standard terms, but important to understand obligations) Step 3: Board resolution authorizing President/Director to sign PPA Step 4: Execute PPA electronically in Partner Connect Step 5: FSA countersigns PPA Step 6: You are now an \"eligible institution\" under Title IV!\tDraft PPA from FSA; board resolution; legal review\tSigned PPA executed by both parties; effective date established\tPPA effective; school authorized to disburse Title IV funds\t$2K-$5K legal review 37-40\tComplete Common Origination & Disbursement (COD) System Setup\tStep 1: Register for COD System access (cod.ed.gov) - COD = system where you report all Title IV disbursements to Department of Education - Required for Pell Grant participation Step 2: Designate COD users (Financial Aid Director, Bursar) Step 3: Complete COD training (online modules) Step 4: Test COD system with dummy records Step 5: Connect COD to your FA software (API integration) Step 6: Establish G5 System access (payment/grant management) - G5 = where FSA deposits Pell funds to your school - Must have separate bank account for Title IV funds only\tCOD registration; G5 registration; FA software API credentials\tCOD system operational; test transactions successful; G5 bank account established\tFSA approves live COD access\t$0 (free system) Month 9-10 Deliverable: PPA executed + COD system live + G5 payment system active + SCHOOL IS NOW TITLE IV ELIGIBLE 🎉 PHASE 3: OPERATIONAL LAUNCH (Months 11-14) Month 11-12: Financial Aid Office Staffing & Student Enrollment Week\tTask\tAction Steps\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tSuccess Metric\tCost 41-44\tHire & Train Financial Aid Staff\tREQUIRED POSITIONS: 1. Financial Aid Director (Required by FSA) - Salary: $55K-$75K - Qualifications: 3+ years FA experience; NASFAA certification preferred - Responsibilities: Oversee all Title IV compliance, student packaging, COD reporting 2. Financial Aid Counselor(s) (1 per 150-200 students) - Salary: $40K-$50K each - Responsibilities: FAFSA assistance, verification, award packaging, student counseling 3. Bursar/Business Office Manager - Salary: $45K-$60K - Responsibilities: Title IV fund disbursement, R2T4 calculations, accounting Step 1: Post positions; recruit experienced FA professionals Step 2: Send new hires to NASFAA training (nasfaa.org) - National Conference ($1,500/person) - FSA Compliance Workshops ($800/person) Step 3: Establish FA office procedures manual Step 4: Subscribe to compliance resources (NASFAA Briefing newsletter, AskRegs database)\tJob descriptions; salary budget; NASFAA training registration\tFA Director hired; 2+ FA Counselors hired; Bursar hired; all complete Title IV training\tStaff demonstrate competency in FA packaging, FAFSA processing, COD reporting\t$140K-$185K annual salaries + $10K training 45-48\tLaunch Student Recruitment & FAFSA Processing\tStep 1: Update marketing materials to include: - \"Accredited by Council on Occupational Education (Candidate Status)\" - \"Federal Financial Aid Available - We Accept Pell Grants\" - Net Price Calculator on website (required by federal law) Step 2: Train admissions staff on FAFSA process - Students must complete Free Application for Federal Student Aid at studentaid.gov - School receives ISIR (Institutional Student Information Record) with EFC (Expected Family Contribution) Step 3: Process first cohort of students: - 100 students enrolled for first term (conservative start) - Average Pell eligibility: $6,000/student - Total Pell funds: $600K for first term Step 4: Complete FAFSA verification (30% of students randomly selected by FSA) - Students must provide IRS tax transcripts, W-2s, proof of identity - FA staff verifies data matches FAFSA Step 5: Package financial aid awards - Pell Grant + any other aid (scholarships, employer support) - Issue award letters to students Step 6: Process enrollment certifications in COD\tMarketing materials updated; FAFSA FAQs for students; verification procedures documented\t100+ students enrolled with completed FAFSAs; ISIRs received; aid packaged; award letters sent\t70%+ of applicants complete FAFSA; 50%+ eligible for Pell\t$20K marketing spend Month 11-12 Deliverable: FA office fully staffed + 100 students enrolled with Pell eligibility + First disbursement prepared Month 13-14: First Pell Grant Disbursement & Compliance Monitoring Week\tTask\tAction Steps\tExpected Input\tExpected Output\tSuccess Metric\tCost 49-52\tFirst Pell Grant Disbursement\tCRITICAL FEDERAL RULES: Disbursement Timeline: - First disbursement: Cannot occur until student has: - Completed 30+ days of program (attendance verified) - Attended all scheduled classes/labs - Passed any required entrance exams - Maximum disbursement: Lesser of: - Cost of Attendance (COA) - EFC - or actual charges (tuition + fees) Step 1: Verify 30-day attendance for enrolled students - Instructors sign attendance rosters - FA staff confirms no absences exceeding 14 consecutive days (triggering withdrawal) Step 2: Calculate disbursement amounts in FA software - Pell is typically disbursed in 2 payments per semester (or proportionally for non-term programs) Step 3: Submit disbursement records to COD system - COD validates eligibility - COD sends funding request to G5 system Step 4: FSA deposits funds to school's G5 bank account (2-3 business days) Step 5: Apply funds to student accounts - Pay tuition/fees first - Any credit balance must be paid to student within 14 days (refund check or direct deposit) Step 6: Disburse credit balances to students RESULT: School receives $600K in Pe"}]},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"[Content truncated — view full chat at source URL]"}]},{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"text":"Source: "},{"type":"link","href":"https://www.genspark.ai/agents?id=be05a4c4-1ee0-4974-a47a-999be3616a02","children":[{"text":"https://www.genspark.ai/agents?id=be05a4c4-1ee0-4974-a47a-999be3616a02"}]}]}]
